is  a  C-glucosylated  octaketide  Abstract:  Carminic  acid  anthraquinone  and  the  main  constituent  of  the  natural  dye  carmine  (E120) possessing unique coloring, stability and solubility properties.  Despite  being  used  since  ancient  times,  longstanding  efforts  to  elucidate its route of biosynthesis have been unsuccessful. Herein is  reported a novel combination of enzymes derived from a plant (Aloe  arborescens, Aa), a bacterium (Streptomyces sp R1128, St), and an  insect  (Dactylopius  coccus,  Dc)  that  allows  for  the  biosynthesis  of  the C-glucosylated anthraquinone, dcII, a precursor for carminic acid.  The  pathway,  consisting  of  AaOKS,  StZhuI,  StZhuJ  and  DcUGT2,  presents  an  alternative  biosynthetic  approach  for  the  production  of  polyketides  by  using  a  type  III  polyketide  synthase  (PKS)  and  tailoring enzymes originating from a type II PKS system. The current  study  showcases  the  power  of  using  transient  expression  in  Nicotiana  benthamiana  for  efficient  and  rapid  identification  of  functional  biosynthetic  pathways  including  both  soluble  and  membrane-bound enzymes.

Polyketides are a class of compounds with enormous structural  diversity,  including  high-value  compounds  such  as  lovastatin  (cholesterol lowering drug), daunorubicin  (chemotherapeutical),  (pigments).[1]  tetracyclines  (antibiotic)  and  anthocyanins  Carminic acid is a C-glucosylated octaketide anthraquinone with  superior industrial color properties in terms of stability, solubility  and  coloring  potential.[2]  Carminic  acid  is  extracted  from  the  scale  insect  Dactylopius  coccus,  which  infect  cacti  from  the  Opuntia  genus.  This  supply  chain  for  carminic  acid  has  remained  volatile[3]  and  is  challenged  by  a  rapidly  increasing  demand  due  to  consumer  preferences  for  natural  colors.[4]  The  chemical synthesis method available is not suitable for industrial  production of carminic acid.[5]  Author affiliation:  [a]  Dr.  J. Currently,  not  much  is  known  about  the  biosynthetic  route  to  carminic acid in D. coccus. Carminic acid has been proposed to  originate  its  anthraqinone structure.[6]  Recently,  an  UDP-glucosyltransferase,  DcUGT2  was  isolated  from  D.  coccus  via  a  combined  transcriptomic  and  biochemical  approach.[7]  The  enzyme  was  shown  to  catalyze  the  C- glucosylation  at  the  C-2  position  of  kermesic  acid  and  flavokermesic  acid  (also  known  as  laccaic  acid  D  or  TMAC  (3,6,8-trihydroxy-1-methylanthraquinone-2-carboxylic  acid)),  to  form carminic acid and dcII, respectively.  In the current study we report the construction of a synthetic de  novo pathway for formation of the C-glucosylated anthraquinone  dcII.  Although  a  combinatorial  approach  has  been  widely  explored  for  polyketide  biosynthesis  in  fungi  and  bacteria,[8]  herein is reported the first example of a successful combination  of  enzymes,  involved  in  polyketide  biosynthesis,  derived  from a  plant, a bacterium and an insect.  DcUGT2 is the only functionally characterized enzyme known to  be  able  to  C-glucosylate  octaketide  anthraquinones,  making  it  essential  for  our  approach  to  construct  a  pathway  for  C- glucosylated  octaketide  anthraquinones.  The  enzyme  is  predicted  to  be  bound  to  the  endoplasmic  reticulum  via  a  transmembrane  domain situated near the C-terminal and this is  important  for  catalytic  activity.  Removal  of  this  transmembrane  region  resulted  in  a  100-fold  decrease  in  activity  of  DcUGT2.[7]

Removal  of  this  transmembrane  region  resulted  in  a  100-fold  decrease  in  activity  of  DcUGT2.[7]  DcUGT2  is  also  reported  to  be  a  glycoprotein  and  thus  undergoes  post-translational  modification.[7]  Bacterial  host  organisms such as Escherichia coli and especially Streptomyces  coelicolor  have  been  engineered  for  polyketide  biosynthesis,[9]  but  their  lack  of  an  endoplasmatic  reticulum  make  them  unsuitable as hosts for biosynthesis involving DcUGT2.   In recent years, transient expression in Nicothiana benthamiana  has  been  shown  to  be  a  versatile  platform  for  heterologous  expression  of  genes[10]  and  for  functional  characterization  of  biosynthetic  genes  involved  in  plant  specialized  metabolism.[11]  Co-expression  of  multiple  genes  encoding  enzymes  involved  in  complex metabolic pathways can be achieved efficiently,[12] and  with  transient  expression,  it  is  possible  to  go  from  gene  to  biosynthetic  product  within  seven  days.[13]  Importantly  for  the  expression of DcUGT2, N. benthamiana possesses an extensive  for  post-translational  modification  of  proteins.[14]  system  Transient  expression  in  N.  benthamiana  has  been  reported  for  the  reconstitution  of  biosynthetic  pathways  of  terpenoids  and  alkaloids.[15]  The  present  study  represents  the  first  successful  utilization of N. benthamiana for polyketide biosynthetic pathway  analysis,  hence,  expanding  the  repertoire  of  biosynthetic  pathways  that  can  be  advantageously  investigated  in  this  organism. In  planta,  the  acyl-CoA  thioesters  are  precursors  of  flavonoids,  fatty  acids  and  lignin[16]  which  are  found  throughout  the Nicotiana genus.[17] Stable heterologous expression of fungal

from  a  PKS-dependent  pathway  based  on  and plant PKS genes in Nicotiana tabacum, has been shown to  result  in  the  accumulation  of  polyketide  products,[18]  suggesting  that  acyl-  and  malonoyl-CoA  precursors  are  available  for  heterologously produced enzymes in Nicotiana species.  Because  the  genes  responsible  for  octaketide  anthraquinone  in  D.  coccus  have  not  been  experimentally  biosynthesis  established, and are thus not available for production of carminic  acid  in  heterologous  hosts,  we  explored  the  possibility  of  combined  use  of  enzymes  from  other  characterized  anthraquinone  biosynthetic  pathways.  Formation  of  octaketides  is  catalyzed  by  polyketide  synthases  (PKSs),  of  which  three  distinct types have been described, type I, II and III, with type III  predominantly being present in plants.[19]  In  bacteria,  PKS  genes  and  genes  encoding  tailoring  enzymes  such as cyclases, oxidases, and transferases cluster together in  the  genomes.  This  genome  organization  facilitates  coordinated  expression  of  polyketide  biosynthetic  genes  resulting  in  the  formation  of  specific  cyclized  polyketides[20]  minimizing  spontaneous cyclization products attributed to the reactive poly- β-keto  structure  of  the  linear  non-reduced  PKS  product.[21]  Cyclases  in  type  II  PKSs  gene  clusters  have  been  successfully  combined  with  non-native  PKS  partners,  resulting  the  biosynthesis  of  engineered  polyketides.[22]  Unexplained  incompatibility  of  cyclase-PKS  pairs  has  also  been  reported.[20,  23]  For internal use, please do not delete. Flavokermesic  acid,  the  suggested  precursor  of  dcII,  has  previously been biosynthesized in Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2)  strain  CH999    by  co-expressing  the  gene  encoding  the  type  II  PKS, 'mini-PKS', from the actinorhodin cluster together with the  genes encoding the cyclases StZhuI and StZhuJ from the R1128  gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. no R1128.[24] Using a single- gene-approach, we replaced the multicomponent ’mini-PKS’ with  AaOKS  from  the  plant  Aloe  arborescens  to  provide  the  linear  octaketide  the  chalcone  synthase  (CHS)  gene  family,  has  been  shown  in  vitro  to  catalyze  the  formation  of  a  linear  octaketide,  solely  using  malonyl-CoA as substrate.[19c] Transient expression of AaOKS in  N.  benthamiana  resulted  in  the  formation  of  SEK4  and  SEK4B  (Figure  1B),  supporting  an  in  planta  function  of  AaOKS,  similar  to  those  previously  reported  in  vitro.[19c]  Expression  resulted  in  the  additional  production  of  a  compound  with  an  m/z  231.0663  ([M-H]-)  corresponding  to  the  heptaketide  aloesone.  Combined,  this  suggests  that  N.  benthamiana  has  none  or  a  very  limited  endogenous  capacity  for  modifying  SEK4,  SEK4B  or  the  linear  octaketide product.  intermediate. Together  with  the  C-glucosylated  aloesone,  aloesin,  octaketide  anthraquinones  such  as  aloe-emodin  occur  naturally  in  A.  arborescens and their in planta formation is thought to involve a  keto-reductase  or  cyclases  utilizing  linear  octaketides  as  substrate.[19c]  However,  due  to  the  limited  genetic  information  and insufficient biochemical protein characterization, none of the  enzymes  responsible  for  cyclization  have  been  identified  in  A.  arborescens.  It  was  therefore  tested  whether  co-expression  of  the  two  bacterial  cyclase-encoding  genes  StZhuI  and  StZhuJ  were able to catalyze formation of the desired cyclization pattern  (C12-C7  and  C5-C14)  from  the  linear  octaketide  produced  by  AaOKS.  StZhuI  and  StZhuJ  have  been  functionally  expressed  in  E.  coli  [25]  and  their  function  tested  in  vitro.  However,  their  in  vivo  activity  has  not  been  shown  in  heterologous  hosts  outside  the  Streptomyces  genus.  individual  co- expression  of  StZhuI  and  StZhuJ  with  AaOKS  resulted  in  a  change in the plant’s octaketide composition, when compared to  the  composition  found  in  extracts  from  N.  benthamiana  solely  expressing  AaOKS  (Figure  1B-1D).  This  demonstrated  that  StZhuI  and  StZhuJ  were  expressed  as  functionally  active  enzymes  in  N.  benthamiana  and  able  to  accept  the  unfolded  non-reduced octaketide product of AaOKS as a substrate. Compared  to  the  previously  reported pathway of flavokermesic acid, where only 30 % of the  octaketide  precursor  was  converted  final  product  flavokermesic  acid,[24]  co-expression  of  both  cyclase-encoding  genes  with  AaOKS  in  N.  benthamiana,  yielded  primarily  flavokermesic acid and O-glucosides thereof. While the levels of  aloesone  and  SEK4B  remained  relatively  constant,  SEK4  was  largely eliminated as a shunt product (Figure 1E). The formation  of  flavokermesic  acid-O-glucoside  shows  that  endogenous  N.  benthamiana  glucosyltransferases  are  modifying  the  formed  flavokermesic acid. These results are  supported  by  a  previous  study  in  which  endogenous  N.  benthamiana  enzymes  were  shown  in  detoxification  of  non-native  metabolites  by  O-glycosylation.[26]  The  detoxification  enzymes  displayed  a  preference  for  non- native metabolites, containing a carboxylic acid group.  From  Streptomyces  coelicolor  CH999,  the  flavokermesic  acid  anthrone  was  not  reported  as  a  product  from  co-expression  of  “miniPKS”,  StZhuI  and  StZhuJ.[24]  Throughout  our  experiments  the  levels  of  the  flavokermesic acid  anthrone  remained  elusive,  when  AaOKS  was  co-expressed  with  StZhuI,  StZhuJ  or  both,  and

This  work  exemplifies  how  combination  of  type  III  PKS  with  cyclases  from  a  type  II  PKS  system  offers  an  alternative  route  for engineering biosynthetic pathways of high-value polyketides.  Bacterial  systems  have  been  well-explored  as  heterologous  hosts  functional  expression  of  membrane  anchored  tailoring  enzymes  and  enzymes that require post-translational modifications in order to  exhibit  biochemical  activity,  like  in  the  case  of  DcUGT2,  are  problematic  in  bacterial  systems.  These  limitations  can  be  alleviated by the use of N. benthamiana, which has been shown  to  be  a  versatile  host  organism  for  the  functional  expression  of  both  soluble  and  membrane  bound  biosynthetic  enzymes,[13, 15a,  15b]  for  which  post-translational  modifications[14]  benefit  the  enzyme’s functionality.   N. benthamiana thus offers the possibility to expand the diversity  of  biosynthesizable  polyketide  compounds  by  combinations  of  polyketide  biosynthetic  enzymes  from  various  organisms.  Additionally, it provides a platform for dissecting and functionally  characterizing individual genes from polyketide gene clusters.    In  this  study  we  demonstrate  construction  of  a  functional  pathway for C-glucosylated flavokermesic acid by co-expression  in  N.  benthamiana  of  4  genes  from  3  different  species  representing  life.  This  establishes  N.  benthamiana as a suitable heterologous host for investigation of  polyketide biosynthetic pathways

by co-expression  in  N.  benthamiana  of  4  genes  from  3  different  species  representing  life.  This  establishes  N.  benthamiana as a suitable heterologous host for investigation of  polyketide biosynthetic pathways consisting of a large number of  biosynthetic enzymes.   As shown here and by others,[27] a caveat of the N. benthamiana  system  when  studying  biosynthetic  pathways  is  competition  between  the  endogenously  enzyme  systems  present  and  heterologously  produced  enzymes  for  pathway  intermediates  and end products. SEK4 is formed by bond formation between C1(OH) and C5(OH) and between  In conclusion, the construction of a biosynthetic pathway for dcII  is  a  major  step  towards  the  development  of  a  biosynthetic  pathway  for  carminic  acid.  Complete  biosynthesis  of  carminic  acid awaits identification of an oxygenase capable of catalyzing  hydroxylation  at the C-8  position of flavokermesic acid resulting  in the conversion of dcII into carminic acid.  All genes described in this study were codon optimized for expression in  N.  benthamiana,  cloned  into  pEAQ-USER[15b]  and  expressed  in  N.  benthamiana  as  described  in.[13]  Metabolites  were  extracted  with  85  %  methanol  +  0.1  %  formic  acid  at  50  °C.  Samples  were  analyzed  on  an  Agilent  1200  HPLC  system  coupled  to  a  Bruker  micrOTOF-Q  II  mass  spectrometer  with  electron  spray  ionization  (ESI)  in  negative  ionization  mode.
